Republican Party strategy against Obama's re-election
Republican leaders have justified their policies with the necessity of fighting electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center calls such fraud a myth, saying that electoral fraud is less common in the US than the number of people who die after being struck by lightning.
In fact, Republican attorneys have only seen 300 cases of voter fraud in the U.S. in the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have been enacting new laws since 2009 that make the process of election or enrollment difficult.
After the November 2010 election, there were 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were submitted in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to submit a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for elections in advance, invalidate the right to register on the electoral roll on the day of the elections and remove the right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required a photo ID to be presented to voters.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The Constitution of the United States was upheld by the Supreme Court in 2008.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this procedure to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have supported proposals for such laws in 34 states to force voters to submit photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e., 21 million people of voting age, do not own any photo ID issued by their state's government office.
Furthermore, about five million new voters did not have such ID in 2012.
In addition, obtaining the required identity card often costs more than one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
25% of African Americans, 15% of people with income under $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their adherence to democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who elect rather Republican candidates to use cards issued by those clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for elections.
The first such request was made by Arizona.
Since 2011, 12 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states backed legislation that would repeal voter registration on election day.
In addition, they have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to enroll.
These limitations have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million residents.
However, measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% drop in new voter enrolment in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans made up 33% of the electorate who voted in advance, even though African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who accounted for 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the passing of laws that restrict voter registration.
Democratic governors have blocked several bills with their vetoes.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, the Attorney General of the United States intervened.
In part, they were able to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the submission of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics speak primarily of the bias of passed laws and see them as an apparent effort to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states where these laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 votes in the Electoral College necessary to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain today: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
