the Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
It is also the last particle predicted by the standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - that has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty that it is a Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have an entirely new particle that closely resembles the Higgs boson as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the large physics congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all the data are still missing so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume that this is a Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems small, and let's look at what it's really about.
There is an unquestionable law in this world that says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
This rule can not be bypassed - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
It also divides the particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently adhere to Pauli's principle.
And at the other end are bosons, vile anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in Berkeley laboratories: mesons, which we leave unnoticed here, and "power particles", with which great natural forces are spread and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is due to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "interference" will arise an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "bearers of force".
A more stable field
It is also the case with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that another field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disconnected" in order for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; for its excitation it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen level of a pond, only a very large boulder will clear.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator of the part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with friendly beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - so that such energy can be developed.
Again, the analogy with the electromagnetic field lends itself to clarifying the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep by itself on the refrigerator.
And it is equally true that not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do so have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) do not.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what is all this research for, what will it "bring to us"?
From a scientific point of view, it is a confirmation of the validity of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any inconsistencies between observations and predictions of SM.
In addition, not many physicists literally want to find them, because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model has huge flaws so far, it does not bring any explanation of gravity (ouch!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe's mass (ouch!).
However, until now, CERN has not found such contradictions.
Responses
The responses of these studies in the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. Novak can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell’s labs had no idea of the revolution their work would spark.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said this - the laser was initially considered such a "toy to the lab".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle did not initially plan it that way, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around the LHC must necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that one really never knows...
Palliative Care: The Best Way to Get Out of Life by Le Devoir
Through his Commission on the Dignity of Dying, Quebek recently became involved in a delicate issue concerning the end of life.
