"But it's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The disease has done its work: his immense weakness makes it impossible for him to go to the toilet alone or to eat alone.
He looks back at the delicious breakfast and agrees to help him eat.
He is courageous and even smiles, talking to strangers who stop by him, bringing him medicines, offering him a bath.
The courage to die a simple death.
"My biggest wish is to get rid of this diarrhea, it humiliates me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
“Throughout one’s life one learns that men pee standing up,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
Returning to the stage of the child is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"Depends on which person's abilities" whether he will accept the return, says the psychologist.
In the opinion of many people who deal with palliative care, the crucial moments take place at the very core of such a return.
Patients who enter a home with Victor-Gadbois palliative care all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who take care of them does not provide them with so-called "medical" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "of suffocation in full consciousness".
But the disease allowed me to discover my children.
“I have good kids,” he adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in my life," she says, and then she allows us to put a breathing apparatus on her.
He is looking forward to his last visit from Italy in the coming days.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, in collaboration with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
This is what palliative care looks like when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 people.
That is very little if we realize that we will all die one day.
Here, life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, for example, a sip of brandy or pepsi can be given to him, to taste.
Diabetics no longer need to monitor their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night they brought beer to Mr. X, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of his late father.
"We are helping patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of care services.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, the days go by one by one, but they do not resemble each other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who rejoices at his last encounter with his family, thoroughly backed up on pillows while being toasted in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies surrounded by his parents, a woman, and two young children after trying every possible way to survive.
“For half a year now, there are always three to five beds that are designed for people with cancer up to 45 years old,” says Dr Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois home come here from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the sick person reaches the final stages of their life, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is precisely this fundamental inaccessibility of healthcare in Quebec that has led many doctors specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, the manifesto has been signed by leaders in the field of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure everyone has access to quality palliative care before euthanasia can be agreed upon.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He is concerned that patients will not be asked to be killed because they do not receive adequate care.
And at the same time, many oncologists take care of their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Her chances of survival were minimal when she left demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted that I had stopped fighting, telling us.
And yet she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative pussy team eased their pain.
However, palliative care is certainly not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Grand Montréal area, patients resist pain management in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether the sedatives are given to him permanently or not.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Sick people who are not given sedatives always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” rather it means “I want you to relieve me of pain.”
