In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are current account book depositors, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed with a double-key encryption system.
The network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to finish this additional line.
This is the cutting-up stage of a file; i.e., the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers will "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then will they "chopping up" the whole thing.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then appear indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If the user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the second one will be abandoned, because each of them has a different imprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited by the number of 21 million, but they can be divided up to one hundred million, so there is room for margin here...
The difficulty of a given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has seen its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and the stored bitcoins have been stolen.
“The loophole used is not related to the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payments company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also monitors money laundering opportunities through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Notable players such as Wikipedia reject donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a ledger of current accounts and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul to convert bitcoin into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but uses the Bitcoin system to authenticate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the carrier manages its identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up with merchants, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just give the address, which can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems and move to more horizontal systems.
“It’s going to be a while before Bitcoin takes over, but 2013 could be a crucial year,” he predicts.
In addition, in its report, the ECB envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
