Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Mohamed Morsi has taken up the next round of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the promulgation of a constitution granting it temporary unlimited powers, it has decided to play the vagabond.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else's opinion, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has used a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal disputes.
This new initiative further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "violate his word" and "undermines the law".
But his supporters say it is a means to tackle the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speed up the transition process.
A referendum will be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time, which will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify the article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while protests sweep across the country.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially since this hastily organised vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: 'Either you approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers', which should otherwise end when the new constitution is approved.
And in this strange atmosphere yesterday, 85 deputies of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was promulgated, they slammed the door, saying that they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have imitated their move.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 alternates were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further wondered that one of the few disputes that day revolved around... hours for prayer, when some committee members held the view that the hours in the boardroom were not properly aligned.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains the same as the 1971 version of the Constitution, stating that "the principles of sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, hoped to replace the term "principle" with the term "rules", which would allow stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” argues the liberals, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
Islamization of the Constitution is carried out through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers an advisory role on al-Azhar University, particularly on issues of checking the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "persons called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
Liberals are even more concerned about the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains generally a civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulams, but university workers, many of whom graduated from French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, they agree that "there may be contradictions in the interpretation of Article 220, since the terms used in it belong to the religious vocabulary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this."
The text approved yesterday is heavily criticized, in addition to religious sites, because of the expanded powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been severely curtailed compared to the former regime.
Another controversial place: the powers vested in the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, proceedings with civilians will not be banned in military courts, as demanded by human rights associations.
These associations talk about their doubts in connection with the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef from Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from a saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort, and the inviolability of nature.
AaF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Bowing to the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who enter this “bath” will receive God’s mercy.
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here too Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers will go through the Way of Pain, or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the judgment took place, passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the crucifixion, to the anointing stone and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place for Jews - the Wailing Wall, the rest of the temple, which was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip around the vertical
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained from a secret hiding place from an enemy that Herod the Great had built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruins are located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are involved in mountaineering can access it on their own.
Others will take the cable car to this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous Hermon ski resort, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on top of the mountain.
Visit the unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can’t visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
The paintings of Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso are widely represented in his exhibition.
In Akkon you can visit the museum-spa Al Basha, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figurines of bath users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dali and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic sites in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are glittering.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
The three main spa resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red Sea and Dead Sea.
Each offers swimming pools, aquaparks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea it is possible to bathe even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest land point of the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
Cyan water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily keeps on the surface even people who can not swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and medicinal mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to heal the jagged nerves.
Touch the mysterious ancient past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
A famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mentions of this city can be found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists love to wander through narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press on the walls in the aisle of "your" sign, luck will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to get their picture taken.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators including Pontius Pilate.
Carefully renovated theatre is used today for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For the trip, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is approximately 3.8 shekels).
The city's main traffic is buses, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem, and there is the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower town with the upper one.
It's basically an underground cableway.
Travelling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, which you can drive for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, work on markets, shops and public transport stops.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels you get only kosher food: except for pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which there are a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various types of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israel.
However, there are a lot of fattened cats that wander gracefully "to their taste".
In the evening you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Cats love populated places and are eager to indulge in every good thing.
The car will cost between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 per day (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - 15 dollars per day.
And renting a bike will cost around 15 shekels per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
To get to know the country and relax came the most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
The Promised Land was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Great and powerful" will announce it to Moscow: emigrants will save money on language
While MPs and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language exams, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling "counterfeit" certificates
13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities every year.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, a law came into force under which every migrant worker will be required to pass an exam on knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, housing and municipal management, lifestyle and retail sales.
However, the FMS promises that in time the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of linguistic knowledge, but also of Russian history and the foundations of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed in order to obtain and extend a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law does not apply to people who successfully achieved attestation and obtained an academic diploma until the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefits, Condemnation and Protection of Rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship between the Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; more than 160 such centers are already open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by members of the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Services).
But before the law went into effect, human rights defenders were able to ask many times in the press the question: and what will it actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all - the representatives of the migration service respond - this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering as a result of "slave labor."
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Chairman of the Board of Directors of FMS Russia in Tajikistan.
Their rights should be protected before they leave.
Only a system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for non-professional emigrants, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, Sebelev says with conviction, the future migrant is doomed to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will secure a "password" to terrible, tight hostels in which he and dozens of others like him will spend months without food and documents and toil for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
"In their homeland they promise them one thing, but upon arrival they cheat them, confiscate their passports, do not pay the promised wages," said Tolib Sharipov, head of the General Administration of Labour Migration.
Don't swear!
Even less so, since many citizens of Central Asian republics who intend to go to Russia for work recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to go to, but they do not even have experience with the work in question.
Of course, it is not so much their fault as their misfortune: only very few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least an adequate basic education.
After all, their families also need to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, put on and equipped for school.
As children reach a productive age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without the knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that with regard to the law on language tests, human rights defenders point to one important thing.
Testing will only be carried out on those migrants who have legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't be taking exams or getting any more official jobs.
In the meantime, most migrant workers are living illegally in Russia as before.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized entry"
Many of the incoming workers say that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all those language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But false registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Employees of the Russian police know that we have basically false documents, without registration, and this results in cases of blackmail.
"They require a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," - a citizen of Tajikistan Umed Khuskadamov shared with journalists about his experience.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that not only migrants’ registration documents were fake.
FMS employees have already confiscated several false certificates of passing the language test.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary color printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, in the hope of facilitating the problem of passing the tests, paid 7,000 rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times higher than the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the near future is to protect the system from corruption, so that workers cannot simply buy documents, in this agree government officials and human rights defenders.
Meanwhile, the government can promise foreign workers who failed the tests for the first time the necessary time to take a course on the basics of the Russian language.
Visitors who do not know Russian are expected to work in areas where active dealing with people is not required.
MVD (Ministry of the Interior) does not take into circulation the illegal arms market
The proportion of crimes involving legally held weapons is very low.
The MVD of Russia presents a proposal to tighten the law in relation to the owners of civilian weapons.
It is the reaction of the government authorities to recent events: the instigation of shootings at weddings, which were done without victims, and the massacre prepared by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which resulted in the deaths of seven people.
The police want to ban the carrying of dangerous weapons in public places and increase the age from which it is possible to obtain a license to carry weapons - from 18 to 21 years.
