In the United States, workers of fast food and supermarkets are on strike
Up to a quarter of all U.S. teenagers will work at McDonald’s.
In recent days, there has been a wave of protests in America against low wages in Walmart hypermarkets and restaurants of popular fast food chains, such as "McDonald", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken".
So far, no one can predict whether this wave will turn into a ninth wave, or whether it is destined to disappear soon.
The whole action is supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing social organizations.
In addition to increasing the modest salaries that ordinary workers receive at Walmart and in fast food systems, the goal of protest organizers is to achieve in them the formation in their trade union organizations.
At present, this economic sector is practically untouched by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
Events began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday" when an orgy of cheap sales hit America, engulfing millions of residents and in some cases accompanied by brawls.
On this day, some of Walmart’s 2.2 million employees worldwide have left their workplaces and demonstrated alongside trade unions and left-wing activists from multinational chain companies whose goods are targeted at lower- and middle-class people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products in its stores are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-wage employees at Walmart only shop at home.
The availability and range of goods has made Walmart one of the largest companies in America.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell goods so cheap in part because they pay their employees little.
They also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of automatic carts or hand scanners.
Demonstrators on "Black Friday" demanded a pay raise, complaining that the cost of health insurance provided by the company rose sharply from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee receives $9.5 an hour, but this does not correspond to the amount of expenses, say the employees.
Researchers at the University of California, Berkeley, show that if Walmart raises its average wage to $12 an hour, it will cost the company $3.2 billion a year.
That’s an average of 1.1% more than the company currently spends on salaries.
If Walmart shifts the wage increase fully to the shoulders of consumers, each visit to the store will cost only 46 cents more.
In a year, customers will spend about $12.39 more than they do today.
Walmart advocates point out that the protest took place in only nine countries and the company should do virtually no harm.
"Black Friday" in the company's stores lasted from 8 p.m. on Thursday through midnight the following day, and during this time Walmart sold about 5,000 items of merchandise per second.
In total, its coffers carried out almost 100 million transactions on "Black Friday".
Company representative Dan Fogelman said in an interview with the left-leaning Huffington Post website that "less than five" Walmart employees had left their jobs, and that the protest was "another media sensation" organized by the union.
"Unoccupied cash register!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their goal was not Walmart department stores (those in the said progressive city are not very popular, and therefore are almost not here), but "McDonald" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, then doesn't even pay you sick and doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage for work in accordance with federal laws and the regulations of the state of New York is 7.25 dollars per hour.
Fastfood restaurants are gradually increasing this wage, but only slightly, and on average, their regular workers in New York City receive $8.90 per hour.
In this expensive city, no one has a lower salary.
I don't quite understand how you can exist in New York for that kind of money.
Almost a quarter of American teenagers who work behind the counter after school part-time and live with their parents pass through the employment at "McDonald".
Few people see it as their main source of income or plan to stay there for a long time.
At present, I constantly meet in an interview with "McDonald" workers who complain that they have to live on this money and sometimes even feed their children from it.
On the other hand, there is a comment on the Wall Street Journal forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday at "McDonald's" on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs in fast food businesses start receiving at least $15 an hour, more than double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade unions be established in the fast food sphere.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing the establishment of labor unions and punishing labor movement activists with bullying and dismissal.
On the other hand, management rarely makes their lives easier.
However, introducing a trade union in fast food companies is also difficult for objective reasons.
One of the main reasons is the extremely high turnover of employees.
Disagree
On that day, there were also loud protests in a number of other cheap Manhattan restaurants.
The climax of the event was a rally at "McDonald's" near Times Square, where several local Democratic politicians spoke, most notably City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald" says he sells billions of servings, and then doesn't even pay you sick pay and doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!"
Demonstrators also received support from other prominent New York Democrats, such as mayoral candidate Bill de Blasio, who said that "we need to come out together to support fast food workers so that they get the fair pay for their work and economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
As described by the New York Times, it was the largest event of its kind in the history of the American fast-food industry.
But only a few hundred people attended, though not all of them were fast food workers, employing tens of thousands of people in New York City.
Whether this event will become the spark that will ignite the flame of the mass movement is still unclear.
“The brain is deluded on average.”
Among fans of modern virtual reality technologies, the topic of augmented reality is popular; recently, this means perceiving the world especially through the prism of special glasses.
Earlier this summer, at its annual conference, Google unveiled a working model for the novelty, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed for the patent.
An interview with the head of the interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft’s Cambridge Laboratory, Sharam Izadi, shows that glasses are a thing of the past for the company’s scientists.
They are attracted by the perspective of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, creating virtual public spaces.
- Please tell us in general what your research group is doing?
We deal with human-machine interactions, but at the same time we try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity is stuck at the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, at most sometimes touching the screen with a finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate significant changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors - this is a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is for sale without Kinect sensors, because the ability to control using gestures is very interesting for everyone.
- What awaits us in the future?
- Despite the fact that the Kinect system transferred the interaction to the physical level, very many interactions still take place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input flow of information has improved (the system receives a larger amount of data), but the output flow has not yet been improved separately.
We are trying to change this, working on truly three-dimensional imaging systems based on various technologies, including projective ones.
It is necessary to let the computer world into our physical world, to make it more real.
However, for this it is necessary to get to know not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to add virtual objects to the real world in a much more appropriate form.
And first of all - to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
This is a popular thing, but is it not overrated?
- Surely it can not be considered a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others in our neighborhood about their activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not about rampant ones, just about such cheap, short ones.
Gestures would not be taken with the camera of the device, but with a bracelet that would track the movements of bones and muscles.
So far it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
In general, however, the future has a mixed type of control, such as gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- How do you ask me to give you this can of lemonade?
You say it and you show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very difficult to spot.
- So you want to get users to adapt to what a machine can or cannot do at a given moment?
- It's not necessary at all, but it's a rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide a fairly good depth resolution, this is very important.
- If you have to talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Is there not enough resolution, depth or something else today?
- Basically the current generation - this is what we can reflect in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 f/s.
But it's not just the megapixels themselves, it's the matrix and the depth.
At the current point of view, all current technologies are insufficient for us - this adds work to the designers of algorithms.
So we have to keep in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also Z.
So the speed, the number of frames per second, is also very important.
Human motion is quite dynamic, and the current data rates of 30 frames per second are frankly a little low, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our Redmond laboratory made the touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, while the current, mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human interaction with the machine.
For me at work would be a very useful equivalent of such a device, I just do not need so many touches, but I need some extra shots per second.
- And increasing the number of cameras is not necessary?
Three cameras are now used in the Kinect system, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other is a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera - this is actually a common visible-band sensor.
It is not used to determine the depth of an object.
More cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or make it worse, because it would increase the necessary volume of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analog system, play with the curvature of the camera location and see how it helps in determining the three-dimensional position.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft (unlike Google) did not publicly present their glasses.
Don’t you think that when it comes to everyday use of augmented reality technology with special glasses, it is one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking and constantly holding the smatphone in raised hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the strongest option would be a "portable" form of reality extension, when it would be possible to switch from glasses to smartphone, projection display and around at any time on the basis of the cloud platform.
Glasses - this is a very personal device, in this is their strength (private things you see only you), and at the same time also weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects at the same time with other people.
Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in "Iron Man", but also to an ordinary mortal.
There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no touch response!
Hands feel nothing!
What are your group’s responses to this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality - this is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the addition of tactile sensations could easily become the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is used - the use of the second hand as a kind of substrate for imaging.
It records compressions in an excellent way!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at adding tactileness to these "pictures in the air" - for example, the interference of several directional ultrasound beams at a defined point where the finger is located, evokes a tactile feeling, but it is still very weak - as if you were blowing on your fingertips.
There is also a bracelet on the wrist that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
To think that he feels what he seems to feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried that yet.
Here is another challenge that will be fought for a long time to come - how to get a person who is physically in a very cramped space to believe that he is walking in an open, practically endless space - we are also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all such as in clubs), moving platforms and also huge balls.
If brain deception becomes a goal, then the work is still for many years to come.
This is what makes virtual reality work so appealing to researchers - many things are in their prime.
