The powers are also similar to some extent, but because Germany has a federal system, it also has these courts of auditors at the level of individual federal states - in this the system differs somewhat from ours.
BRH can control only federal money, represented by state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by our regions and municipalities, are controlled there from the level of the federal accounting courts.
As far as the legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, however, in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, but it cannot be said for sure that it is better in everything.
Is it because they have better controls?
Certainly not, but again, I don't like comparisons like that.
But it must be said that even the countries we see as role models are facing a whole range of problems.
Otherwise, it would be of no use to them to cooperate with our office, would it not?
As for domestic legislation, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office?
Due to the fact that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet appeared in our control actions.
Because we do ex post checks, we have to expect a certain delay.
So far, we are only observing this in the process of preparing future inspections - we have started our new tool for "risk detection of waste", through which we have passed almost 14 thousand public contracts, and we have analysed them - there, of course, these changes will manifest themselves, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tender will be adjusted, and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law to be a benefit or an additional burden on the system of bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope that it will be confirmed.
The problem here may be that the rules will be "tightened" and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Already under the previous rules, the audited persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the Regional Council) to ensure that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does the law need to be tightened in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, not punish those who commit formal misconduct that does not affect decision-making.
Such a system will only create more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how do we get out of this?
Let's see where the road doesn't lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with checks on the so-called "scratch system" - and what does that mean?
Is the svarcsystem disabled or allowed?
After all, the law must be set somehow, and if it prohibits something, even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activity of the office, which has the duty to go to check and enforce obligations.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it," but he can't say we're going to do anything like that.
There are rather strict rules in the Public Procurement Act as to what is to be formally done - which is the right thing to do to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the bidder with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - this is what I think is missing.
