In May, we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, so we will definitely prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, when we are in the USA, would like to combine this with a performance in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalist, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of disabled people.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as terrible as it seems at first glance.
We have five members in an electric wheelchair, her trolleys have to travel in the luggage compartment, and of course we carry a large amount of cargo and tool boxes with us...
However, so far it has always been done without problems, ČSA and British Airways were well prepared for us, I was surprised how many times.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was without problems.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare how the individual differs in accessibility, public access to disabled people and the like.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than in our country, we have seen that in the East everything is still in its very beginning.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person on an electric wheelchair to move around the city center by himself.
There is no such thing as a wheelchair in the elevator.
Fortunately, there are already civic associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And what do we still need to catch up with the more advanced countries?
There's a lot of things we're still behind on...
But it is important to mention that improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of the people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public, they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life there, on the contrary, we are a bit ahead with The Tap Tap!
Respecting the public or being barrier-free is one thing, but it’s only when we become great athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers that things really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but let’s go back a few years, what made you decide to start it in 1998?
I joined the Jedlička Institute as an educator, where I had many young people around me who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play saxophone, among other things, so together with my colleague I started a music club.
And over time, as our host Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
But popularity has only come in recent years, am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us when we started to connect with well-known singers and also actively work on promoting the band.
We realized that the work that cannot be seen, in fact, did not exist.
Moreover, thanks to contributions from the European Union, we can afford quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was your goal to get The Tap Tap this high?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something different.
Show business is overcrowded with things where one mimics the other.
In a way, it is logical, everything new is accepted carefully and takes a long time.
Things that are rare are very few, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a man who sees us for the first time is, of course, regret, it is natural...
But that regret is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not suffering from all the abandoned beings that we have to feel sorry for.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means to do so.
I say that when something happens to people with disabilities, it’s not just for them, but for society as a whole.
Did being a strict boss, as many people have called you, also help this success?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and require a certain discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic idea and a head in the clouds, and when they find that they have to go to rehearsal twice a week, run out of medicine and spend a lot of time on the road to concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and that wants to achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has 20 members.
How many of them were at its beginnings in 1998?
Only one Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people leave and come, there is no way to prevent that.
Those who have the will and desire always have the door open.
