Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this European space agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been involved in a number of Agency projects over the years.
However, the journey of Poland to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before the Second World War; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, a lecture by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entering the Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listener cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for Entering Cosmonautics in France.
The mentioned doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
In 1925, a railway was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used to start the train or to brake it.
Information about this Druze is known only from the period press.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to deal with rockets.
The research was provided by the Armament Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzycki.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozinski, appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work of the Rocket - an air torpedo and air bomb by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Advisczo-Naukowy) was involved in all projects for the military use of missile technology.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended the beginning of the war.
After the war, other works devoted to space science appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, in which there are four more comprehensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded 1951), and already in the autumn, PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first chairman of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the highly successful RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch occurred on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with an access of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were started in the Bled desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next development type was supposed to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have access to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
In 1962, however, further development was suspended.
The first RM rocket was the Meteor-1, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B, and -1C) were developed, differing in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, space was available with a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the development of the Meteor-2 rocket was carried out at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland’s accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space research on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively debate in public.
It will be interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In effect, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labour, (wages) there is a price tension.
By this term it is necessary to understand the situation when the manufacturer tries to compete with imports of cheap goods by "undercutting" the price of a competitor in order to pull a larger market share and thus increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to transfer production abroad, or to buy cheaply there, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the social expenditures of the state necessarily increase.
The whole situation is aggravated by the absolute unwillingness of businessmen to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage he has done in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that there is no need to provide specific statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies where national governments are forced to enter into competition with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments are putting their own populations at risk for private capital, regardless of the social downturn.
This is mainly reflected in changes to existing laws.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the price diktat of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done both by a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment, and by limiting workers' rights in the field of labour law.
The result is increasing poverty, along with a growing gap between the poor and the rich.
There have been public food outlets in Germany for many years for the poor, who cannot make a living from their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common that properly employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them to an existential minimum.
Such a scandal was also reported in the case of the auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
Undoubtedly, the austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states lead to the same situation in which people, under the pressure of a catastrophic fall in the social level, are forced to either emigrate as they did in the 19th century, or to languish for hungry wages on the fringes of society in the hope that private investment may one day come to the country.
But here we have to ask, where does it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian, or an African are still working for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to Latin America as a whole.
Liberal theories and the media have argued that the state cannot capitalize on its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists strongly on the opinion that the state must not interfere with the economy by controlling interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, now actually governs politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is the clear answer, yes.
The evidence is the existence of a virtually all-powerful and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, providing mutual benefits, legislation, where practically everything is punishable, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to lack of funds, commission the drafting of draft laws to private law firms that are closely related to industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
All power in this way does not come from the people, as the constitutions of the Western type proclaim, but from financially strong groups preferring their own interests.
It is clear that liberal democracies are now rapidly coming into the situation described by Appianus in his Crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in complete decay and the authorities have occupied themselves with violence.
For bribes, for the illicit acquisition of favors, and for the use of stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were rampant, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote...Character people did not run for office at all, so once, as a result of this disruption, the state was without consuls for eight months.....It began to talk about the fact that the only remedy in a bad situation was self-government, and that one had to choose an energetic man.
Conclusion As in antiquity, contemporary society is based on a ruthless preference for self-interest regardless of the general social interest.
Private capital, by its very nature, is no longer able to understand and apply the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is now, as it was then, an unprecedented decadence of the elites without any attempt at reform of a deeper nature.
The causality of the rise of both fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the demise of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracy can be seen as a kind of break with the expectation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that today’s elites completely ignore in the future the possible hundreds of thousands of lives lost, the humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing, along with the crimes against humanity, as we know them from ancient and new history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and internal European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the state's capital participation in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
