Controversial EU regulations include compulsory incorporation of bio-fuels, which is harmful to nature as a result, a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain relatively small amounts of a dangerous substance, or a directive on the size of chicken cages, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
The de facto ban on the use of the term spread butter or the exclusion of classic bulbs from sale was also previously criticised.
Bananas should be at least 14 cm long.
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that trade or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or a group of states (so the Czech Republic now also enforces the demands of its banks with a veto threat).
