I wonder why we still need a library.
They all have internet, iPads and e-books.
None of these old-style libraries are going willingly anymore, are they?
Spijkenisse, a housing estate in close proximity to Rotterdam with no job opportunities of its own that are not even worth a visit, holds a special record.
This municipality with 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to resolve this stupid situation, a few years ago the decision was made to contribute to general education and to build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes.
But the success of the educational offensive was nothing short of staggering.
And so the city councillors recognized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, a master of insanely bold column charts and maker of witty, often even cynical buildings, accepted the matter with the usual calmness and appeared at a competition meeting in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around and shrugging its shoulders, the cheeky Maas piled his gifts on himself according to size and ended his activistically justified speech with the words "Dear Town!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was climbed for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground car park, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Small-town grey, which so far could not offer more than a post-modern pedestrian zone and an extremely ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy, is thanks to this richer by a little contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
A Long Way to a Book
First impression: Eldorado reading under the cheese lid.
Although there is an elevator in the middle of the mountain massif, you will discover real spatial and reader’s passions only when conquering the topography on foot.
On all sides, the glass interior is bright and clear, the floor of the burnt cab and elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, there are bookcases along the facade, and in the middle is a large dark space that is mostly awkward and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the space for the reader from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is skillfully used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a home technology exchange.
A special delight is the black book shelves, which are one wall paneling, one window sill, and another railing of the stairs.
The appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Even sworn architects and civil engineers shake their heads over an unknown building material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials here,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
So one day we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years, a millimetre fleece of synthetic material has been used under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is cheap and time-efficient.
Thin textile lasts one or two seasons and is then ripe for disposal in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantity - was pressed onto boards four centimeters thick.
Due to the heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and loadable material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
There are 105 steps to get to the top.
At the end of a nearly 500-meter journey, you will be rewarded in a literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and ficuses in pots.
They take care of the atmosphere, but mainly the right humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but this house, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," Trouborst says.
It is heated and cooled by the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass lid, the sun shines in only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden trusses, which stand perpendicular to the glazed facade, serve as a shading and capture a large part of the sunlight.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest can handle fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls Boekenberg the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every city dweller was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal fund.
First, optical gaps were to be filled in the previously not fully equipped library, which currently numbers 70,000 pieces.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are completely full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship to the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
This made MVRDV successful in the royal discipline, which is called identity formation in professional jargon.
Spijkenisse wrote a history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated he is.
This is, after all, the starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained from the vote on Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is teetering on the brink of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first signalled that it would vote against the proposal for Palestinian observer status in the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza
But now Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it will support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting on the creation of a no-fly zone.
It was eventually adopted by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason for this is that they are now changing their foreign policy, away from a policy that was, so to speak, controlled by the US, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is all the more difficult because Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
The Germans are between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still settling in, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It shows readiness to take positions in the case of national interests that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The economic interests of Germany are to some extent different from the economic interests of other powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did economic interests influence attitudes in the Middle East conflict and voting in the UN?
First, Germany has large outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, they must be careful not to frighten the public, but also the elites in Arab countries.
That plays a role anyway.
But I don’t want to give it too much importance, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
This, however, plays an important role in German thinking.
Did Germany’s relations with the US hurt when Germany abstained from both important decisions, for example in the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe and even in the USA there is a great deal of sympathy for the German position.
That is why I do not think it was as dramatic a turning point as it was for Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even earn some respect from this.
This signals that he must be considered an international player and his interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the other hand, voted in favour of the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of U.S. domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration has a secret understanding of the European position.
But, of course, as a result of the political situation there, this position cannot be held publicly.
I think that differences of opinion are not really as big as they always seem.
When you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all happy with Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US, on the one hand, and with the position of the most important partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that's what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not happening at the moment.
So they can’t be part of a wider line and must instead push things forward from their own position.
That’s what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Does it even want to take the lead?
Or is the leadership role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult to play a bigger role.
For example, if we look at the European crisis, every time Germany takes on a larger role, anti-German sentiments arise.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
It’s actually an old problem: we don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be acceptable to all sorts of neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
The US influence in European politics is now steadily declining, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more popular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America study together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
