Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What Are the Most Serious Sexually Transmitted Diseases?
Bacterial SPIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common viral SPIs are HIV, human papillomaviruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Cucumbers and scabies belong to the parasitic SPI.
Who is among the most affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur primarily in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, sexually transmitted diseases that occur frequently are chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (mold), gonorrhea, and human papillomaviruses.
HIV is relatively low among heterosexual adults in our country, but about 20 percent of newly infected people are HIV-positive.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections occur significantly more often than in other groups of the population.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, human papillomaviruses are often found among adolescents.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases need to be reported.
The number of people infected with syphilis has more than doubled from 1,697 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of people newly infected with HIV has been decreasing since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of STDs?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, difficulty urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen and blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain undetected.
How can we protect ourselves?
The danger of infection can be reduced by condoms, but they do not offer 100% protection.
For the agents of sexually transmitted diseases can be partly transmitted by infection from impurities and by close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially in the case of frequent alternation of sexual partners.
In the case of early diagnosis, it is possible to cure most of the SPI and prevent later consequences.
