But as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, who is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011) says.
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription relating to boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there's the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After seeing the research literature and demonstrating the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me but I was unable to do it".
Boredom is distinguished from apathy by the fact that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there is no urge to do anything in apathy.
He says that the core of boredom is "disrupting the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and the feeling of slowly passing time."
Boredom can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated TV program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the television program quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but were not sure why and attributed these difficulties to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like finding the wrong parts on a factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.”
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and doodleing, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help with boredom to fight and keep people physically more attentive.
"Research shows that children who are allowed to fidge are more likely to learn and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We've all experienced boredom at times - the delay of my flight, the buzzing speaker, the particularly lengthy film.
Some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists in the 1980s developed the Boredom Proneness Scale.
The scale includes questions like, "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
Teenagers, however, are generally inert.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which nearly 400 teenagers and their parents were contacted seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren’t at school.
3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know if the percentage of boredom would be now, 21 years later, higher or lower.
But he said he knows that "growing up is the peak time for boredom", which is largely due to the fact that children and youth are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: "Is boredom good for you?".
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form, it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble or abuse addictive substances as a way to mitigate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
“Boredom is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn’t always know the best thing to do.
If you are bored and use this energy to play the guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a moment, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will no longer be bored, but he will not learn how to entertain himself or drive himself, said Professor Fenske.
And "this separate management is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain themselves, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn’t be too critical of it either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of the reach of constant activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We accuse her of needing to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
What people are actually looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy their free time.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to have fun when the noise turns off."
