Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I'm a conservative."
It is not just university students who are being challenged for their opinions.
I don't remember ever dreaming of studying at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother studied at a university that I thought was the world’s largest seat of knowledge, a modern-day wrapped Greek symposium motivating the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
At the end of the 1980s, within two weeks of joining Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my bags and rushed into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I gave up because I objected to loving students in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson has eloquently stated that I left because I was forced to drink from battered cups.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I escaped because I was subject to systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for only one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
