Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of students to the right of the center are suffering similar persecutions.
The institutionalized and growing hatred against conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students demanded the same protections for equal rights as gays, people with disabilities and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Younger Years Association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College claim that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, exposed to personal attacks, and made to feel unwelcome".
They call for the creation of a position on the university's Equal Opportunities Committee to ensure that their views are freely communicated.
Their situation was not helped by the recently released BBC Two documentary Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right about student politics, which portrayed conservatives as weirdos and neo-Nazis.
The show featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who rode a Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit, and had a cane with a silver head.
At other colleges, conservative students say they are treated as "scapegoats" because of the introduction of higher tuition.
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told a Sunday newspaper that "left-wing influence in universities is growing.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without ever meeting us."
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who is behind the movement for greater protection, says such a climate is "unpleasant," while 19-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in the attitude of JCR members toward people to the right of the center.
"This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion, as well as to the well-being of members," he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford, I was a minority about one member.
I joined in September 1986, 18-year-old and cripplingly shy.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was the most ferocious.
A year earlier, the university had voted against awarding the honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher because of cuts in higher education funding.
Even the Stalinists would shudder from the atmosphere.
During the first few days of the opening week, when the new students were meeting with each other and with the professors, I got to taste the wormwood that was to come.
I have found that not only do professors tacitly approve of the taunting of conservative pupils, but they are also eager to participate.
A policy of mining strike, privatization, and government resistance to apartheid sanctions in South Africa was brought into the wood-covered auditoriums.
My first lecture was about translating an 18th-century French text into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I was pretty stiff.
Professor Pitt, a little man with a face like cake dough, was very bile.
"The Thatchers refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students nodded.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you're too busy with social matters," Professor Pitt growled.
I went back to my room in shock.
At dinner at school, I sat alone when I felt a slight tap on my shoulder.
He was a sophomore named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, that's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be worse for you.
Most conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour.
