The world's toughest trade: the sulfur carriers in the Kawah Ijen volcano area
For four euros, carriers in the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by conquering sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, it has to tow to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulfur gases leak from the interior of the Earth and when in contact with the air it passes into a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
To the top of the volcano, which rises 2,386 meters, it is only 250 meters, but it takes over 40 minutes for exhausted carriers to climb at a turtle's pace upwards, because they maintain balance and carefully consider their steps so as not to slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine
When they are upstairs, they make their way past the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and they tire of carrying heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
PT Candi Ngrimbi has been mining the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for making matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even sugar bleaching.
"Because it's common to carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and is ruined at the end, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
Even if it seems like a negligible amount for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wage of the miners here is very high. For example, for the collection of coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day, and the salary for a fortnight is two million rupees (167 euros), " explains the carrier, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a mason.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so difficult, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he's not breathing well, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, the sulfur of which has already begun to take its toll on him, despite his face being protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's got bad breath, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases escaping from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’m going to work for two more years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French,” he promises.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man afflicted by fate could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a receptionist in a hotel, and instead does the work of a porter.
