We are the worst in the world in the reproduction of our population, so we felt it was a topic we had to touch on.
We knew that the government was trying a lot of things, like expanding perfumes with pheromones or organizing dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like the composition of rap, to solve this problem."
1.2 children
The one who does not take it lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and allocates financial benefits.
All of these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy city state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore due to population stratification is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered a recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Department of Marriage and Family of the National Bureau of Population, says this is due to "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
“People have a wider range of options when it comes to life goals and priorities, it’s not just about marriage and family,” he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the postponement of marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
While there have been efforts under immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against population decline, this has generated resentment among the local population.
Some Singaporean websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and little effort at integration.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore's governing party recorded its worst electoral result since independence.
After the elections, there was an effort to solve the problem with quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending and immigration policies, there have also been some unexpected consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to affect the real estate business.
The Office for Urban Development has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as "boot boxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in sales.
However, there is concern that these apartments may support a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of developer EL Developers, says their “shoeboxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
“They’re more popular by selling them days to weeks faster than larger homes.
That’s why they’re so much better for our cash flow.”
However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too Stressed
Singapore is a city state.
Although these new rules could lead to an increase in the nation’s birth rate, an interview with Singaporeans working in a financial district in the city centre suggests they won’t have much effect.
"People are always stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, which is why many people put it off," says the young official.
“Let the others have children.
But for me it is important to rely on my own money and time,” says another, about twenty-year-old, young man.
Both men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force its citizens to have children, it is still Singaporeans who have the last word on starting a family.
What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any intrusion.
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he posts things on the Internet that he certainly would not tell anyone in ordinary communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely personal" on a personal level and a "user name and password" when it came to social networks.
“I wouldn’t disclose my biggest secret,” Jorge, 10, says in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he’s had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
“I’m putting pretty pictures on FB, or pictures of us playing.
I also talk to my friends there.
I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine, or a photo that would make someone laugh,” she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, photos of naked persons or photos of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 of the friends he has on Facebook and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
“I created a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends," she says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone he didn't know.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits he doesn’t know 20 people from his friends list.
“I’m not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to this boy, none of them were encouraging him to do anything, nor did they ask for his address or phone number.
“If they push me or require me to do so, I will simply remove them from my account,” he said.
José logged on to Ask after reading the recommendations on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
A friend of mine was being blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he confirmed.
According to Jose, the victim did not log out of the account.
"You've just activated a private regime."
It then explains a series of steps to set up your account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in awkward or awkward situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
“I know it’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that children and adolescents need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
He states that: "The Internet originated as a means of finding information, but when social networks emerged, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are still learning," he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it".
Also, to be - as far as the environment is concerned - prudent, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is is to ask questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do something doesn’t work,” he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your photo the way you posted your friend’s?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you tag the people in the party photos, did you ask permission from them?
Does everyone always need to know what you’re doing?
The next point is to realize that they must behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
“A person outside the Internet is guided by respect, morality and other principles, and it should be the same on social networks,” he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-grade teacher and educational advisor, explains that it is necessary for parents of children to read the rules of social networks carefully.
“If they understand every trick, they have a good basis to talk to children about the consequences that setting up an account on the Internet can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers".
South American Summit Ends and Lima Declaration Not Published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru today ended without the Lima Declaration being issued, which was announced and allegedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to gain access to the document signed at Unasur's sixth meeting of heads of state and government, but representatives of both the State Department and the presidential office, who initially set out to publish the document after the summit ended, said it would later be published on the Peruvian government's website.
They further stated that the content was published by Peru's President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video from the presidential assembly without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "Confidential session, audio transmission prevented".
A small amount of the information available to journalists was provided by the press spokesmen of some governments who were present, but not by Peruvian spokesmen.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of participating presidents, prompting a backlash from hundreds of journalists from various national and international media asking for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency e-mailed the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but this is only President Humala's statement, and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA) and even on this occasion the originally promised Lima Declaration was not published, despite being eagerly demanded by the press.
On the official ASPA website, it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasts for all journalists, but completely blocked the flow of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with a joint commitment from Chile and Peru to adopt the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
Peru's President Ollanta Humala and Chile's President Sebastián Pisera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing the two sides' defence speech on Monday to discuss the dispute that Lima has initiated against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing in this international court today," said President Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful dispute resolution, conventions and international courts,” he added, greeting President Humala with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would comply with the ruling of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia accepted the Bogotá Pact this week, thus expressing compliance with the rulings of the International Court that ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered the ruling entirely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with starting the morning speeches and concluding the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read a final document in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and activity was planned on 31 projects between South American countries, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements, he said that UNASUR member states would take “important steps toward the goal of South American citizenship, for which residency agreements are being expanded.”
He said actions were being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil insecurity and international organized crime, to improve drug availability and the cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to take joint and effective action against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, “economic consolidation is not meant to be a victory, but to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future,” Humala said.
"We have decided to prioritise a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve the transport connections of various places in South America, especially rural and border areas ... so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties," he said.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two more relate to a better connection with Ecuador, but he did not give more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return it to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said ahead of his attendance at the regional meeting that he hopes to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico on Saturday to discuss with respect the International Court of Justice ruling on the maritime border dispute being contested by Bogotá.
"I may meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow," Santos said.
"We will discuss all solutions, none are excluded, not even a treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and considerate way possible," Santos said.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday for the inauguration of President Enrique Pena Nieta.
As part of the summit, EU defence ministers met provisionally to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the region's defence.
UNASUR members are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim president of this regional bloc.
Rafael Correa: South America must learn integration from Europe
Ecuadorian President Rafael Correa announced today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case indeed, must learn from Europe".
Correa, who attended the sixth South American Union of Nations (Unasur) presidential summit in Lima, told state TV Perú that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are practically one homeland."
In this sense, he advocated a project to create South American citizenship, which Unasur member countries support.
“Freedom of movement of citizens and workers within any South American country that is already taking place among members of the Andean Community must be achieved, however, there are still backward areas that want to return us to the past,” he said.
The Ecuadorian president said he agreed to a regrouping of the Organization of American States (OAS) on condition that the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states is reduced and that those who signed the San José Pact on Human Rights are taken into account.
"Those in the lead never commit to anything, and we South Americans, on the contrary, sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights in Washington is funded by the United States," he said in reference to political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
President Correa confirmed that he did not regret the decision because it did not betray his principles, and he respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He added that at the time "there were reasonable suspicions that Assange could be extradited to a third country regardless of the ongoing process".
In addition, he criticized the Swedish justice system, which asked him to be questioned in Swedish territory over an alleged sexual offence, with "Sweden's own legislation allowing the interview to take place by videoconferencing call that could take place from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa said there was a risk that Assange's physical and mental health would deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he was at our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had minor lung problems, but nothing serious," the Ecuadorian head of state said.
"But he is at risk of getting worse physically and mentally because he is confined in a small space with no possibility of movement in the fresh air.
It would affect everyone’s health,” he added.
President Correa noted that the settlement of asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London on the basis of a permit allowing him to travel to Ecuador is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and European courts, and stressed that talks have been held with London to resolve the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
"We don't negotiate on human rights, we don't use that word in this case, but there have been constant talks.
The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European courts, because Assange’s lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is leading a series of proceedings in various European instances,” he said.
He said: "If the UK issues a pass tomorrow, it will all be over."
And if Mr Assange is heard by Sweden at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as the legislation there allows without any problems and as has already been done in other cases, tomorrow this problem will be put to an end."
Correa took advantage of the situation to present himself as a defender of freedom of the press, making it clear that he certainly does not tolerate "underaverage, bad intentions and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
“The greatest enemies of a free press are not us, vile and depraved politicians, but bad journalists at the service of profit, coercion and blackmail,” he said.
From this point of view, he expressed his joy at the fact that neither such journalists, nor bankers, nor hegemonic countries, nor bourgeoisie control Ecuador, and he announced that if he was re-elected, he would "continue to make changes along the right path and in the right direction".
President Correa also supported the decision to further maintain the veto expressed by Paraguay over Unasur union membership until at least her next election, arguing that the whole "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and putschism shrouded in legality" because it in fact "destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
In addition, Ecuador's president said he considered it "completely appropriate" to wish his Colombian counterpart Juan Manuel Santos to negotiate with Nicaragua on maritime borders between the two countries now, in the wake of the ruling by the International Court in The Hague in favour of Nicaragua.
The judgment is not accepted at this time.
“This is a problem between South America and Central America.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They need to be assessed broadly to be overcome and to be able to move forward."
He also expressed hope for a settlement of the maritime border dispute, which he is resolving in the same court in Peru and Chile, and expressed the view that "it is right for Latin America to seek international instances if both countries pledge to accept the judgment, however harsh it may be".
Regarding the possibility of running in the next presidential election in Ecuador to run for a third term, he noted that he perceives this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult".
Correa has stated that if he loses the election in February 2013, he will retire from public life.
“I personally have never been interested in power, but situations as unfair as socio-economic poverty in Ecuador can only be remedied by political power.
My political movement believed that it was I who guaranteed this likely victory, so we must accept this responsibility," he said.
“If I won, it would be my last term as president and then I would leave politics.
If we lose, it's the same for me.
I have already made my decision," he said.
Correa also mentioned the new health treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
“I have just spoken to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro, who says that President Chávez has left for scheduled routine treatment and his return to Cuba was expected after the campaign ended.
This is not a relapse in the health of the president," he explained.
The head of state of Ecuador attended the sixth summit of the heads of state and government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which was concluded with calls for greater regional integration in order to maintain development, equality and security.
AIDS victims today are the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if lightning had struck me," he recounts, recalling a moment of truth the doctor was trying to "soften up a bit," but apparently without success.
The boy kept it a secret from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to learn about it, and with such a commitment that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the earliest patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several struggles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options, and more stigma.
At the time, the director of the Mexican Social Security Institute's (IMSS) clinic did not say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
Back then, AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive and live fully with this syndrome.
However, there are a lot of people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused the destruction of the organism and debilitated the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS first appeared in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, “significantly succeeds that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people,” said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara, with this information being confirmed in an April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients who are diagnosed with the disease, while those who do not use drugs are better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells can live up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that a person who is diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, "live without problems up to 75 years while adhering to the treatment," the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although the death toll has fallen significantly in recent years and the number of people dying from AIDS in Mexico has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the yearbook of the United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far this May. However, since 2005, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured.
Why do people continue to die as a result of the disease?
"It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it's happening at the hospital.
For at least the last 12 years, we have not exhausted the supply of drugs. The problem is that patients come in a very advanced stage, because they do not know the state of the disease, that is, in the late stage of the disease."
He adds: “Nine out of ten patients come when a co-infection has occurred. The only thing that needs to be done in order to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore to offer large-scale tests to detect the disease to all those who ask for it.”
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco, as well as patients such as Fabrizio, who came to have tests done in a private laboratory just because a friend of his had done it, and despite his young age, he has already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi’s sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
“If I’m going to die, I’d rather go out three times a week,” they say, but that’s not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthy, I exercise, I take medication."
To this day, all his parents know is that he suffered from cancer.
“I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I pay attention to myself and to the other person," says Fabrizio, who accepted the invitation to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO daily, so that today, as part of the World AIDS Day, he will motivate those who are afraid with his testimony.
"Let them take the test. If they've taken the risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, it's better. And if they've been diagnosed, let them realize they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
His message sums up the battle against AIDS this year.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who researches information on the HIV virus.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that are doing this task, "there has really been an increase in the distribution of condoms, they used to give us one or two, today they give us packages and hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most susceptible to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question filled with irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy employees, and medical personnel who teens want to avoid, the reporter says.
He proposed to change this ineffective distribution, not just behind the counters, but in dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
“It’s not promiscuity.
Nor is it about "paying for beer and a motel," as Governor Emilio González responded to the question of whether he would agree to distributing condoms in his district.
It is best to make condoms available to those who already lead a sex life," he noted.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
There were 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS cases and 1,317 HIV cases).
In Mexico, the condition ranks fourth in new and detected cases of AIDS and 13th in HIV-related cases.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% blood and 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are four to five people who do not know about the disease per registered case.
The judgment approved by the United States Court of Appeals, which does not recognise Grupo Vitro’s bankruptcy debt restructuring in Mexico, sets an unfortunate precedent for any national business with branches in a neighboring country and a solvency problem.
So it seems that the procedures for restructuring companies, which are allowed by Mexican law, do not apply in the land of stripes and stars, despite international agreements.
The approval of the verdict issued last June 15 by Judge Harlin Hal at the bankruptcy court for Northern Texas leaves Mexican companies without defense against the possibility of confiscation of their property on the other bank of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for the main Mexican glass manufacturer to the United States Supreme Court with an appeal against three irregularities.
To begin with, while the judge of this case claims that creditors should abide by the United States Insolvency Act, the Fifth District Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, it would show ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
In essence, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created to determine the organization of the American Law Institute by an arbitrator.
Second, the judgment provides that without the voting of the branches from the internal corporate structure, where the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority for approval of the restructuring would not have been reached.
However, Mexican law allows for this.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first to adopt this scheme.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, for whose in-house debts the Federal Insolvency Institute vouched.
Furthermore, it is true that even after subtracting the votes of the branches, the creditors - who stood against Vitro in the United States, i.e. the funds of the "suppos" such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergenceia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have achieved a majority.
In the vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37.
This information is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From another point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of the severe economic crisis that has struck the United States.
In the meantime, the family firm González Sady will file an appeal for a new assessment directly with the Court of Appeal so that the assessment takes place in full participation, i.e. with the participation of five judges, as only three originally voted.
If it fails here, it will seek review of the process by a higher instance, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
What is significant about the case is that the court omitted a document sent by the Mexican government as amicus curiae detailing Vitro’s bankruptcy procedure and pointing out that the company had eased itself by adhering to the agreements signed by the two countries to confront the law in question with Chapter 15 of the United States Insolvency Act.
In addition, it is pointed out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, that is, the rules for international insolvency cases that guarantee equality for both debtors and creditors.
Impact on both sides: punishment for Vitro and the state.
Overall Rating
Unnoticed on the table for several months was a criminal complaint from the Mexican aviation union against former owner of the business Gaston Azcárraga Andrade, who was accused of fraudulent conduct, and according to the union of pilots, the container had already overflowed.
An instance headed by Carlos Díaz Chávez Morineau has just filed a lawsuit against the National Banking and Securities Commission, which he accuses of obstruction in the pursuit of justice.
According to her, the Audit Office systematically refused to report to the General Prosecutor’s Office about the transaction carried out by this entrepreneur, in which it collected 198 million pesos from IXE bank from fideicomis F/589 on behalf of the Mexican aviation company.
The funds were most likely directed to the purchase of shares of the Professional Hotel Administration (Administradora Profesional de Hoteles).
Azcárraga Andrade is known to be the majority shareholder of the Posadas hotel chain.
The Siege of Dragon Mart
At the Universidad de Caribe, a group of domestic and foreign environmentalists, academics, entrepreneurs and ordinary citizens met over the weekend to prevent the opening of the Chinese Dragon Mart in Cancún.
We are talking, as is well known, about a huge trade and distribution center with products from the "big wall country" aimed at Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean, which at the bottom would include a residential zone for employees from 150 companies.
Previously, Canacintra (Cámara Nacional de la Industria de Transformación) had managed to unite the governors of the southeastern zone to oppose a monumental site that would partially devastate protected areas and which represents the origin of all resistance to industry.
End of ACTA
The Senate’s request, which was not taken into account by the government and which demanded an explanation of the conditions and circumstances under which the Mexican ambassador to Japan signed the Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement, known under the English acronym ACTA, has become obsolete, according to the Mexican Institute of Industrial Property (Instituto Mexicano de la Propiedad Industrial).
As we know, this happened despite the fact that the Senate itself ruled out the possibility of considering it a threat to freedom of expression on social networks.
Homex in the long run
In an effort to pay off long-term debts and not affect short-term ones, the developer Homex is giving out 500 million pesos worth of investment certificates to the market.
This series is the first of four identical ones to offer interest payments every 28 days.
Competition is born.
The merger of leading companies in information technology, such as NYCE, e-Quality and Kernet, gave birth to an association with the trade name Competition, whose goal will be the software services market in Central and South America.
Investment in the business will exceed $1.5 billion.
Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been involved in the sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has.
Reyes was passionate about the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior, BSN National Basketball League player, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón National Basketball League team, or president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation, before being caught in a wheelchair stroke in 2008.
“I’ve played a lot of roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, general manager of the national team and chairman of the federation,” Reyes recalled during a visit to Primera Hora newspaper reporters at his home in Bayamón, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his faithful wife.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs from his long career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the Heart
With the greatest movement of all, he guards those that commemorate his time in los Vaqueros since the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or team owner.
"It was my best years, I enjoyed it the most because I had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with the Los Vaqueros team since 1967, whether as owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship in 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his BSN debut.
The team was then taken over by "Cuco" Ortiz, who was an excellent leader," Reyes said.
"I remember Gene Bartow, who used to be a coach here and was at the University of Alabama at Birmingham at the time, saying to me, 'I've got a tall two-meter player for you.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended me to point guard Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our top scorers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy brings Bayamon victory in the championship, then Gauss will contribute to the next one."
The championship, when for the team los Vaqueros played Gauss, enjoyed, but only at a distance, because in 1988 he was already the president of the basketball federation.
At that time, he wanted to fully devote himself to his functions and enjoy Mincy's place in the national team.
"I remember the first time we beat the United States in a qualifying Olympic match in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, but we were supposed to have bronze if it wasn't for the Canadian umpire who let us repeat the final throw in," Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He is among the best, as well as the one who defeated Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team in the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and blew out the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that blew us bronze at the World Cup.
That team had not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López, and "Piculin" (Ortiz), but also there were the youths (Javier) "Tocito" Colón and James Carter, the León brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not have been on the team in 1990 due to a knee injury.
The team that may not have had a perfect line-up but managed to win us a gold medal and bring great joy was the team from the 1995 Olympic qualifiers in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players eliminated due to a skirmish in the Pan-American Games in Mar de Plata, we won gold despite all the predictions.
What was the best player in Puerto Rico?
This was without a doubt the Piculin Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one from Puerto Rico has achieved such results at this level as Piculin.
Not to mention his involvement in the various leagues in which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
That's very hard.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I love the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your greatest accomplishment in the Federation?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early 1990s the BSN National League had up to 17 teams in one season.
What did you fail to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by region.
For example, the guys from Ponce would only play in their area and compete with teams from other corners of the island only in the national playoffs.
Now children travel a lot and play too many matches, which is not necessary.
I also see benefits in mandatory certifications and courses for coaches, referee assistants and referees.
I'm glad.
What do you do now?
I listen to music the most, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren and sometimes go to basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, is world renowned for starring John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the Dallas television series, in which he portrayed a man who acted recklessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the Dallas television series became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new Dallas series, died, according to an official family announcement provided to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros., on Friday afternoon from complications associated with cancer.
"Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved best," the family said in a statement.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who represented his wife in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman the moment he died in a Dallas hospital," her agent Jeffrey Lane said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented and I will miss him terribly.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest," Linda Gray said in the announcement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found on his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before Dallas, Hagman made a name for himself on television as a decent guy in NBC's light-hearted comedy I Dream of Jeannie from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a genie) played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live together.
He was also the protagonist in two comedies that were only broadcast briefly, namely The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His acting in films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman’s masterful performance in the form of the incredibly repulsive J.R. that led him to the star peak.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who Shot Jayar?", which was supposed to raise expectations about the emotionally charged episode when Hangman's character is nearly murdered, caused not only a huge amount of speculation by viewers around the world, but also risking millions of dollars in betting offices.
It also helped this piece achieve a record in viewership.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers. Dallas thus became the second most watched entertainment show in history after the end of the broadcast of the MASH series in 1983, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin and J.R. got pregnant, and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiable greedy man with a charismatic smile: a crafty businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), who was an alcoholic, to be locked up in a rehab center.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on his headstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should read, "Here lies honorary citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only thing that didn't work out for him.
Victoria Principal, who starred in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on and off the screen".
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of admirers in the world and in the hearts of all of us who have been lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas series aired on TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five episodes of season two have already been completed and a sixth has just been filmed," the network said in a statement.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there was no statement from Warner or TNT about how the series would proceed.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shined in classic works such as the musicals South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when she gave birth to Larry in 1931, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck in the New York theater scene and then served in England with the Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
There he met a young Swedish designer, Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in Malibu, California, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he published the autobiographical book Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't put anything there that I knew would hurt anyone or hurt them in any way," he told the Prensa Asociada news agency.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital helping fearful patients.
"I advise them, I encourage them, I meet with them when they go into surgery and afterwards," he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of "don't worry, it'll be a little uncomfortable for a while, but you'll be healthy".
He was also an activist in the fight against smoking and participated in various campaigns.
Starts a course that explores the "end of the world"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to do a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long count" of the Mayan calendar, due on December 21, had caught many people as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what lay ahead for him in the next few months: Catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the budget gulf that some call the "debt Armageddon," and the growing conflict into which Israel is drawn, the place where, according to Christians theorizing about the end of the world, the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey this week.
When a person discusses what is happening in the world today, as if we have 30 days left, it is a really good time.
And remember, bad is good for the apocalyptic mind.
And this is not the only professor who offers courses on the "end of the world" in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker holds a course on "Resources, Culture, and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We discuss why these ideas spread over time," he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that control certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war could break out.
This month, students analyze films with apocalyptic themes and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
"I've been trying to inform students about what's possible, likely, plausible, and impossible," Vacker says.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, professor of Latin American history Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, assistant professor of art history and anthropology, came together to organize a course with the simple name The End of the World.
"We're not adding '2012' because we're always counting on the opportunity to re-arrange the course if the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "threatened doom", students must study, create projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the very evening of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"He stretched out into two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, of which 35 applied.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails asking if there was still room.
Students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
Therefore, apocalyptic, worldly, or religious thinking is only a matter of consolation or absence.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in psychology and nursing, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of an hour where it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But none of the students interviewed, let alone the professor, said they believed in the end date of December 21.
"Our first project dealt with the Mayan prediction and we are somehow disproving it," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point on the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that goes back several centuries, with people reacting to changes in their surroundings with predictions about the end of the world.
The rise of this speculation was caused by the internet.
“People don’t think about it anywhere else,” he said.
This is true in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who lectures this year in the Philippines, when asked if he knew of any course on “the end of the world” there, answered quickly.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception at the top office.
We have mercy from the Pope.
Restall noted that many days of the Last Judgment have been talked about over the years, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
The date is taken lightly by both students and professors.
Several have said they intend to go to the "end of the world" festivities.
“I think I’ll call a few friends to laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
